What's next? That hinges on how Benioff responds and how good Salesforce's earnings look.

Plus the activists can't do much without the support of $CRM's largest investors like Vanguard BlackRock Fidelity T. Rowe Price Geode Morgan Stanley Fisher UBS and Wellington.
The letter itself included demands like: Salesforce remove "all references to stakeholder capitalism." https://t.co/qW2UYFdrHM

6️⃣ Strive Asset Management

Co-founded by "anti-woke" ex-presidential candidate Vivek Ramaswamy  the firm wrote a letter to Benioff demanding that he pull back on Salesforce's social messaging and focus on profit.

Notably this isn't Jeff Smith-led Starboard's first run at a SaaS business. 

In 2019 Starboard targeted Box taking a stake as high as 8.8%. Starboard ultimately lost the subsequent hard-fought proxy battle at Box. 

Could Smith try again?

5️⃣ Starboard Value

Its involvement in Salesforce goes back to October when the firm revealed it had taken a “significant stake” in $CRM. 

Sources say Starboard has been disappointed in Salesforce's expense management but isn't pushing for a sale of Slack as others have.

The sources added the firm would like to see CEO Benioff focus more on succession planning and expense management. 

On March 1 Elliott reportedly nominated a slate of directors to Salesforce's board.

Elliott's previous tech targets include PayPal AT&T Dell and Twitter. In 2022 Elliott struck a deal that landed senior portfolio manager Marc Steinberg on Pinterest's board. 

Its intentions in $CRM are fuzzy but sources say the stake is a “multi-billion” investment.

4️⃣ Elliott Management

Among the most prolific activist investors in recent years the firm often goes for the jugular fronted by Jesse Cohn and Paul Singer. 

It will often seek board representation.

Inclusive which focuses more on social investing as compared to ValueAct owns 1.6 million shares of Salesforce SEC filings show. 

They're likely to be more passive than say Third Point.

3️⃣ Inclusive Capital

Jeff Ubben founded Inclusive after co-founding ValueAct in 2000. He launched Inclusive Capital in 2020 and has been busy. 

He was appointed ExxonMobil's board in 2021 and has been building up a massive holding in industrial wood pellet-maker Enviva.
The details of ValueAct's $CRM stake remain unknown Salesforce has yielded somewhat already. On Jan. 27 the company added ValueAct CEO and CIO Mason Morfit to its board.

2️⃣ ValueAct

While the firm doesn't frequently go public with its investing plan the firm recently revealed a stake in Spotify. 

That combined with its involvement in Salesforce suggests it's currently taking aim at macroeconomic-rattled tech giants.
The size of Third Point's stake and the full scale of its intentions at Salesforce haven't been confirmed but Loeb's capable of launching a fearsome proxy fight.

1️⃣ Third Point

Led by billionaire investor Dan Loeb it's launched few high-profile fights including: Disney Campbell Soup and Shell. 

In 2020 Loeb took a stake in Intel launching a campaign that led to Pat Gelsinger's rise to the CEO role and the ousting of Bob Swan.

So far the list includes: 
- Third Point
- ValueAct
- Inclusive Capital
- Elliott Management
- Starboard Value

And it always seems to grow. The latest addition: "anti-woke" Strive Asset Management.
